,Recommended,252690,22904115,"Posted: 10 May, 2016",all,rodneyorpheus,"Negatives:The interface does have a bit of a learning curve.The network functions take some setting up if you want to GM a game, and you'll probably have to open a port on your router - this will require a little bit of technical knowledge, but if you are into GMing RPGs via the Internet, you probably can handle this.No built-in voice chat or video.Costs money.On all these counts its main competitor (Roll20) is vastly superior.Howver, if you want to play tabletop RPGs via the Internet, and you're prepared to pay for it, this is still definitely the way to go. Why?Positives:Built-in (free) rulesets for several popular games, including D&D 3.5, Pathfinder, Numenera, etc.Official support for D&D 5 Edition, and all its suplements and adventures.Loads more rulesets, adventures, and community modules available - in particular I would highly recommend the Savage Worlds ruleset, it works amazingly well if you want something that's not standard D&D.Drag & drop between rulesets, character sheets etc. Drag a skill from the rulebook to your character sheet - bingo, it is automatically set up for you. Drag your character's weapon on to an enemy token - combat modifiers are all automatically applied and damage calculated. This feature alone is worth the price of admission. I can't emphasise too highly just how great this feature is. Once you've tried it, there's no going back.Roll20 and other competitors are free(ish) so why would you pay for this instead?I was originally GMing using Roll20, but I quickly found that to do anything interesting with it I needed to subscribe. And a year's sub ended up costing me more than buying Fantasy Grounds would. So in the end I dropped my Roll20 sub and switched to this, and it actually works out to be much better value for money.This is definitely far and away the best solution if you want to get the true pen & paper expereince over the Internet. I can't recommend it highly enough.Note for Mac users: DO buy the Steam version of the main game, it's by far the easiest way to get it working on a Mac. However do NOT buy the DLC on Steam, none of them will work on Mac. Buy the DLC using the Store button in Fantasy Grounds itself, that WILL work."
