,Recommended,252690,31340053,Posted: 24 April,all,Yagisan,"In this review I would like to first clarify what Fantasy Grounds is, and is not.Fantasy Grounds isn't a traditional game. In fact, it isn't a game at all. It is a virtual tabletop that allows you to play traditional role playing games over the Internet.By default it supports a variety of tabletop games. By supports it means that if you buy the prewritten modules (highly recommended) or type in the rules yourself (time consuming and not recommended) you can play these games online, with other people.It is certainly functional without buying a single module, but I think you'll agree that buying a premade module for your game is a better use of your time. Unfortunately due to licensing costs, modules from some publishers such as Wizards of the Coast (Dungeons and Dragons) are rather expensive.One of Fantasy Grounds great strengths is that it can automate many of the tedious tasks that bog down traditional games, things like automatic experience point calculations, applying combat effects and so on. Once you get over the initial learning curve, it becomes quite easy for the Game Master to design and run an encounter.There are 2 options with Fantasy Grounds, a regular or ultimate license. If you have the same Game Master for every game, buy the ultimate license. It is a site license that allows unlimited free (Demo) license to connnect and play. Players never have to spend any money.It is very important to realise that only modules owned by the Game Master (who is hosting the game) can be used. Players CAN NOT share modules with their Game Master.If you are looking at this as a player, I would suggest having the Game Master buy the Ultimate license, and the players gifting the needed game modules to the Game Master. Players should then use the free Demo license to connect.Happy Gaming."
