,Recommended,252690,17299361,"Posted: 30 July, 2015",all,Marswipp,"If you're not used to playing table top RPGS, the price tag on the base license may seem indimidating at first. It is about what you would pay when purchasing one or two books in any given rule set.Here is what you get with the base license:The ability to connect to any paid license able to host a game.The ability to host any paid license.3.5E rule set with enough open game content to host.4E character sheet and one game module.5E character sheet and basic rules.The core of the d20 rules (CoreRPG).Fate Core SRD ""book"" and character sheetNumenera character sheetPathfinder rule set with enough open game content to host.A default selection of tokensA default selection of portraitsThis does not mean you cannot connect to someone hosting one of the other supported rule sets--or a custom one for that matter. The game masters can and will share the game-specific player content. Thus, only the game masters may actually need to purchase additional content, depending on what they choose to host.Overall, my opinion is that the utility far outweighs the price."
